effectiveness of minority civil rights organizations and their legislative allies. He finds that the organizations’ legislative priorities are consistent with black and Latino preferences for stronger enforcement of civil rights policy and immigration reform. Although these groups focus mainly on civil rights for blacks and immigration issues for Latinos, their policy agendas extend into other significant areas. Minta concludes with an examination of how diversity in Congress helps groups gain greater influence and policy success despite many limits placed upon them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxSocieties, etc. 0aCultural pluralismxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aHuman rights advocacyzUnited States. 0aLatin AmericansxCivil rightszUnited StatesxSocieties, etc. 0aMinority legislatorszUnited States. 0aPressure groupszUnited States. 0aPublic interest lobbyingzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  arace, racism, african american, hispanic, latino, advocacy, advocate, activist, activism, capitol hill, political, politics, poli sci, politician, blm, black lives matter, naacp, civil rights, unidosus, minorities, minority group, america, united states, mainstream, young people, lobbying, lobbyist, progress, progressive, immigration, legal issues, controversial, congress, diversity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226765440423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226765440/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles